  "body": "[comment]: # (Please replace ... with your information. Remove < and >)\r\n\r\n### User Story\r\n\r\nAs a user I want plurals to be displayed correctly for my language\r\n\r\n### Description\r\n\r\n[comment]: # (Feature or Bug? i.e Type: Bug)\r\n*Type*: Feature\r\n\r\n*Summary*: The i18n library we are using supports label pluralization and will display a different text depending on the value of `count` parameter. However, the rules that determine the plural type based on that parameter are specific to English language where:\r\n\r\n| count | type | example|\r\n|---------|-------|-------------|\r\n|`count == 0 ` | `zero` | There are no messages|\r\n|`count == 1`  | `one`  | There is 1 message      |\r\n|`count > 1`    | `other` | There are X messages |\r\n\r\nOther languages have different rules - e.g. in Serbian any number that ends with 1 but doesn't end with 11 is treated as `one`. So, for example applying English rules in a Serbian localization for 21 we would get `other` instead of the correct `one` and the translated text would look awkward.\r\n\r\n### Solution\r\n\r\n*To solve the issue:*\r\n\r\n1. Add pluralization functions for all languages. To avoid duplication reuse the function for languages with the same pluralization rules, see links below.\r\n2. Update all translation file entries that contain plural specific translations. If you add new plural types, copy the previous \"other\" value. Always keep \"zero\" as a separate case.\r\n3. Correctly translate plural specific entries for one language you are familiar with (native level or equivalent). Please choose **exactly one** language and note which one in the PR description.\r\n4. We only care about cardinal integers. Please ignore any rules regarding ordinal numbers, decimals, fractions, etc.\r\n\r\n\r\n### Additional Information\r\n\r\n- Our i18n library - https://github.com/AlexanderZaytsev/react-native-i18n\r\n- Plural rules by groups (without plural type names) - https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Mozilla/Localization/Localization_and_Plurals#List_of_Plural_Rules\r\n- Find the type names here - http://www.unicode.org/cldr/charts/latest/supplemental/language_plural_rules.html",
